TY  - JOUR
T1  - Antecedents and Consequences of Project Team Cross-Functional Cooperation
AU  - Pinto, Mary Beth
AU  - Pinto, Jeffrey K.
AU  - Prescott, John E.
Y1  - 1993/10/01
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.39.10.1281
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.39.10.1281
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1281
EP  - 1297
VL  - 39
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Cross-functional teams can greatly facilitate the successful implementation of projects. This study examined the influence of a set four antecedent constructs (superordinate goals, accessibility, physical proximity and formalized rules and procedures) on the attainment of both cross-functional cooperation and perceived project outcomes. Through the use of path analysis, the results indicated that superordinate goals, physical proximity and project team rules and procedures have significant direct and/or indirect effects on project outcomes through influencing cross-functional cooperation. Further, cross-functional cooperation was a significant predictor of both perceived task and psychosocial project outcomes. Directions for management practice and future research are discussed.
